        "title": "[Feature]: Channel Broker Phase 2B Telegram migration proof",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Adds the Phase 2B Telegram broker routing proof on top of #86133 and #86096.\n- Normalizes Telegram topic shorthand in the broker plugin, including `broker:telegram:<chat>:topic:<id>` and numeric `<chat>:<topic>` targets.\n- Canonicalizes outbound broker session routes to `telegram:<chat>?threadId=<id>` so topic routing is stable without importing native Telegram internals.\n\n## Rollout Context\n\nCloses #86110\nRelated #86108\nRelated #86105\nStacked on #86133\nStacked on #86096\n\nNative Telegram defaults stay unchanged. Existing target-prefix ownership still keeps `telegram:` owned by the native Telegram plugin when that plugin is installed; this PR proves the opt-in broker route through `broker:telegram:...` and the broker alias path when native Telegram is absent.\n\nFor review, the focused stack diff is:\nhttps://github.com/100yenadmin/openclaw/compare/feat/channel-broker-conformance...feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n### Behavior\n\nOpenClaw can route a Telegram topic through `channel-broker` without Telegram extension code. The broker receives a normalized platform `telegram`, conversation id, and thread id; OpenClaw keeps the session route canonical and leaves native Telegram prefix ownership intact.\n\n### Environment\n\n- Local checkout: `/Volumes/LEXAR/repos/openclaw-channel-broker`\n- Branch: `feat/channel-broker-telegram-routing`\n- Head: `40a181b5b2 Add Telegram broker routing proof`\n\n### Steps\n\n1. Sent a synthetic message to `broker:telegram:-1001234567890:topic:42` through `channelBrokerPlugin.message.send.text`.\n2. Verified the provider request used `platform: \"telegram\"`, `conversation.id: \"-1001234567890\"`, and `conversation.threadId: \"42\"`.\n3. Resolved the outbound session route for the same target.\n4. Verified the route canonicalized to `telegram:-1001234567890?threadId=42` and preserved channel chat semantics.\n\n### Evidence\n\n- `pnpm exec vitest run extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.test.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/conformance.test.ts --config test/vitest/vitest.extension-channel-broker.config.ts`\n  - 2 files passed, 10 tests passed.\n- `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit -p extensions/channel-broker/tsconfig.json`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check extensions/channel-broker/src/target.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.ts extensions/channel-broker/src/channel.test.ts`\n  - passed.\n- `pnpm exec oxlint extensions/channel-broker --format unix`\n  - passed.\n- `git diff --check`\n  - passed.\n\n### Observed Result\n\nTelegram topic routing is represented by broker-owned target normalization and provider request semantics, not by core importing or calling native Telegram extension internals.\n\n### Not Tested\n\n- Live Telegram Bot API traffic; this PR is the opt-in broker migration proof, not a live provider connector.\n- Full local suite. Per `/Volumes/LEXAR` policy, broad validation is left to GitHub Actions.\n\n## Current Upstream Gate Context\n\nPR #86096 currently has one unrelated `checks-node-agentic-agents` CI timeout in `src/agents/model-catalog-visibility.test.ts`; the failed test is outside this broker stack. I attempted to rerun the failed job, but GitHub blocked it because this account does not have repository admin rights.\n",
